ina and the Meaning of Brown -- tThe Rural-Urban Matrix in the 1950s South: Rethinking Racial Justice Struggles in Memphis -- tNew York, Puerto Ricans, and the Dilemmas of Integration -- tPart IV Life, Law, and Culture in Post-Brown America -- t‘‘Stretching Out’’: Living and Remembering Brown, 1945–1970 -- tThe Supreme Court’s Two Principles of Equality: From Brown to 2003 -- tBrown v. Board of Education and Its Impact on Black Education in America -- tConclusion: Brown and Historical Memory -- tBibliography -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPerhaps more than any other Supreme Court ruling, Brown v. Board of Education, the 1954 decision declaring the segregation of public schools unconstitutional, highlighted both the possibilities and the limitations of American democracy. This collection of sixteen original essays by historians and legal scholars takes the occasion of the fiftieth anniversary of Brown to reconsider the history and legacy of that landmark decision. From the Grassroots to the Supreme Court juxtaposes oral histories and legal analysis to provide a nuanced look at how men and women understood Brown and sought to make the decision meaningful in their own lives.The contributors illuminate the breadth of developments that led to Brown, from the parallel struggles for social justice among African Americans in the South and Mexican, Asian, and Native Americans in the West during the late nineteenth century to the political and legal strategies implemented by the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (naacp) in the twentieth century. Describing the decision’s impact on local communities, essayists explore the conflict among African Americans over the implementation of Brown in Atlanta’s public schools as well as understandings of the ruling and its relevance among Puerto Rican migrants in New York City. Assessing the legacy of Brown today, contributors analyze its influence on contemporary law, African American thought, and educational opportunities for minority children.ContributorsTomiko Brown-NaginDavison M. DouglasRaymond GavinsLaurie B. GreenChristina GreeneBlair L. M. KelleyMichael J. KlarmanPeter F. LauMadeleine E. LopezWaldo E. Martin Jr.Vicki L. RuizChristopher SchmidtLarissa M. SmithPatricia SullivanKara Miles TurnerMark V. Tushnet  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aSegregation in educationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Civil Rights.2bisacsh1 aBrown-Nagin, Tomiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevins, Neal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDouglas, Davison M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGavins, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraber, Mark A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreen, Laurie B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelley, Blair L. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelley, Blair L.M.1 aKlarman, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLau, Peter F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLau, Peter F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLópez, Madeleine E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Waldo E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiles Turner, Kara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuiz, Vi